## Set up Firebase Authentication in a Next.js App Router project

### 1. Pre-flight checks
- Confirm you have a Firebase project. If not, create one at https://console.firebase.google.com.
- Check if another auth solution is installed (`next-auth`, `@clerk/nextjs`, `lucia`). Remove it first to avoid conflicts.
- Decide which sign-in providers to enable: Google, GitHub, Email/Password, etc.

### 2. Enable Firebase Auth providers
- In the Firebase console, go to **Authentication > Sign-in method**.
- Enable the providers you need (e.g., Google, Email/Password).
- For Google: no extra config needed. For GitHub: register an OAuth app at github.com/settings/developers.

### 3. Install dependencies
```
npm install firebase firebase-admin
```
- `firebase` — client SDK for browser auth flows
- `firebase-admin` — server SDK for verifying tokens in Server Components and API routes
- Do NOT install both `firebase` and `firebase-admin` in the same file. Client and server are separate.

### 4. Get Firebase config
- In the Firebase console, go to **Project Settings > General > Your apps**.
- Click **Add app** > Web (`</>`), register the app, and copy the `firebaseConfig` object.
- Go to **Project Settings > Service accounts**, click **Generate new private key**, and download the JSON file.

### 5. Environment variables
- Add to `.env.local`:
```
# Client SDK (safe to expose — these are public identifiers)
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_API_KEY=AIza...
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN=your-app.firebaseapp.com
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID=your-app
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET=your-app.appspot.com
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID=123456789
NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_APP_ID=1:123:web:abc

# Admin SDK (server-only — NEVER expose to client)
FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID=your-app
FIREBASE_CLIENT_EMAIL=firebase-adminsdk-xxx@your-app.iam.gserviceaccount.com
FIREBASE_PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN PRIVATE KEY-----\nMIIE...\n-----END PRIVATE KEY-----\n"
```
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix is required for client-side vars. Admin SDK vars must NOT have this prefix.
- The `FIREBASE_PRIVATE_KEY` newlines must be escaped as `\n` in `.env` files.

### 6. Initialize the Firebase client SDK (`lib/firebase/client.ts`)
```ts
import { initializeApp, getApps, getApp } from 'firebase/app';
import { getAuth } from 'firebase/auth';

const firebaseConfig = {
  apiKey: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_API_KEY,
  authDomain: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN,
  projectId: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID,
  storageBucket: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET,
  messagingSenderId: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID,
  appId: process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_APP_ID,
};

// Prevent re-initialization during hot reload
const app = getApps().length ? getApp() : initializeApp(firebaseConfig);
export const auth = getAuth(app);
export { app };
```
- `getApps().length ? getApp() : initializeApp()` prevents the "Firebase App already exists" error during Next.js hot reloads.

### 7. Initialize the Firebase Admin SDK (`lib/firebase/admin.ts`)
```ts
import { getApps, initializeApp, cert, getApp } from 'firebase-admin/app';
import { getAuth } from 'firebase-admin/auth';

const adminApp = getApps().find(a => a.name === 'admin')
  ?? initializeApp(
    {
      credential: cert({
        projectId: process.env.FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID,
        clientEmail: process.env.FIREBASE_CLIENT_EMAIL,
        privateKey: process.env.FIREBASE_PRIVATE_KEY?.replace(/\\n/g, '\n'),
      }),
    },
    'admin'
  );

export const adminAuth = getAuth(adminApp);
```
- Name the admin app `'admin'` to distinguish it from the client app.
- The `.replace(/\\n/g, '\n')` is required because `.env` files escape newlines in the private key.

### 8. Auth context for client components (`context/auth-context.tsx`)
```tsx
'use client';
import { createContext, useContext, useEffect, useState } from 'react';
import { User, onAuthStateChanged } from 'firebase/auth';
import { auth } from '@/lib/firebase/client';

interface AuthContextValue {
  user: User | null;
  loading: boolean;
}

const AuthContext = createContext<AuthContextValue>({ user: null, loading: true });

export function AuthProvider({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState<User | null>(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);

  useEffect(() => {
    const unsubscribe = onAuthStateChanged(auth, (firebaseUser) => {
      setUser(firebaseUser);
      setLoading(false);
    });
    return unsubscribe;
  }, []);

  return (
    <AuthContext.Provider value={{ user, loading }}>
      {children}
    </AuthContext.Provider>
  );
}

export const useAuth = () => useContext(AuthContext);
```
- Wrap your root layout with `<AuthProvider>` to make `useAuth()` available everywhere.

### 9. Implement Google sign-in
```ts
import { GoogleAuthProvider, signInWithPopup, signOut } from 'firebase/auth';
import { auth } from '@/lib/firebase/client';

export async function signInWithGoogle() {
  const provider = new GoogleAuthProvider();
  const result = await signInWithPopup(auth, provider);
  const idToken = await result.user.getIdToken();
  // Send idToken to your server to create a session cookie (optional)
  return result.user;
}

export async function signOutUser() {
  await signOut(auth);
}
```

### 10. Implement Email/Password sign-in
```ts
import { createUserWithEmailAndPassword, signInWithEmailAndPassword, sendEmailVerification } from 'firebase/auth';
import { auth } from '@/lib/firebase/client';

export async function signUp(email: string, password: string) {
  const result = await createUserWithEmailAndPassword(auth, email, password);
  await sendEmailVerification(result.user);
  return result.user;
}

export async function signIn(email: string, password: string) {
  const result = await signInWithEmailAndPassword(auth, email, password);
  return result.user;
}
```

### 11. Protect Server Components and API routes
- Get the ID token client-side and pass it as a header:
```ts
// In a client component, before calling a protected API
const idToken = await auth.currentUser?.getIdToken();
const response = await fetch('/api/protected', {
  headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${idToken}` },
});
```
- Verify it server-side in a Route Handler or Server Action:
```ts
import { adminAuth } from '@/lib/firebase/admin';
import { NextRequest } from 'next/server';

export async function GET(request: NextRequest) {
  const idToken = request.headers.get('authorization')?.split('Bearer ')[1];
  if (!idToken) return Response.json({ error: 'Unauthorized' }, { status: 401 });

  const decoded = await adminAuth.verifyIdToken(idToken);
  // decoded.uid is the Firebase UID
  return Response.json({ uid: decoded.uid });
}
```

### 12. Create session cookies (optional, for SSR auth)
- For full Server Component auth (no client-side ID token needed on every request), use session cookies:
```ts
// Create cookie after sign-in
const idToken = await user.getIdToken();
await fetch('/api/auth/session', {
  method: 'POST',
  body: JSON.stringify({ idToken }),
  headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
});

// /api/auth/session/route.ts
export async function POST(req: Request) {
  const { idToken } = await req.json();
  const expiresIn = 60 * 60 * 24 * 5 * 1000; // 5 days
  const sessionCookie = await adminAuth.createSessionCookie(idToken, { expiresIn });
  const response = Response.json({ status: 'success' });
  response.headers.set('Set-Cookie', `session=${sessionCookie}; HttpOnly; Secure; SameSite=Strict; Max-Age=${expiresIn / 1000}; Path=/`);
  return response;
}
```

### 13. Verify the setup
- Run `npm run dev`.
- Click the Google sign-in button — the OAuth popup should appear.
- After sign-in, `useAuth().user` should be populated.
- Call a protected API route and confirm it returns 200 with the correct UID.
- Sign out and verify `useAuth().user` becomes `null`.

### Common errors & fixes
- **`auth/invalid-api-key`** — The `NEXT_PUBLIC_FIREBASE_API_KEY` is wrong or missing. Copy it exactly from Firebase console.
- **`auth/unauthorized-domain`** — The current domain is not in Firebase Auth's authorized domains list. Add `localhost` (for dev) and your production domain in **Authentication > Settings > Authorized domains**.
- **`auth/popup-closed-by-user`** — The user closed the popup. Handle this gracefully in a try/catch — it is not an error.
- **`Firebase App named '[DEFAULT]' already exists`** — Hot reload initialized the app twice. Use the `getApps().length ? getApp() : initializeApp()` guard (step 6).
- **Admin SDK: `Error decoding custom token`** — The `FIREBASE_PRIVATE_KEY` newlines are not unescaped. Ensure `.replace(/\\n/g, '\n')` is applied (step 7).
- **Admin SDK: `FIREBASE_PRIVATE_KEY is not defined`** — The env var is not set on the server. Check `.env.local` (dev) or your hosting env vars (production).
- **Token expired (401 after 1 hour)** — Firebase ID tokens expire after 1 hour. Call `user.getIdToken(true)` to force refresh, or use session cookies (step 12) which last up to 2 weeks.
- **`auth/network-request-failed`** — A network or CORS issue. Check browser network tab for the failing Firebase request.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT prefix Admin SDK env vars (`FIREBASE_CLIENT_EMAIL`, `FIREBASE_PRIVATE_KEY`) with `NEXT_PUBLIC_` — this exposes your service account credentials to the browser.
- Do NOT use `firebase-admin` in Client Components or files imported client-side — it is server-only.
- Do NOT hard-code Firebase credentials in source code — always use environment variables.
- Do NOT call `initializeApp()` without the `getApps()` guard in Next.js — hot reload will throw on the second call.
- Do NOT trust the client-side `user.uid` alone on the server — always verify the ID token with `adminAuth.verifyIdToken()` before granting access.
- Do NOT skip `sendEmailVerification()` for Email/Password sign-up — unverified accounts are a security risk.
- Do NOT store the raw private key JSON file in your repository — add it to `.gitignore` immediately after downloading.
